text: I build decks with other people playing them in mind. It’s fun to min/max but it’s even more fun watching someone who doesn’t know the nuances of a deck figure them out. I also build my decks in a sort of Rock Paper Scissors fashion, having a circular array of decks whose strong point is another decks weak point. Makes for good games and less salt.

Yeah, I generally try to avoid decks that would make for an unfun experience for he average random stranger. That's not to say stax or mld or hand disruption can't be fun for some groups, but by and large I'd guess the average casual player doesn't want to deal with that in a game with a rando, so I try to avoid things like that myself. I keep my counterspells to a number where I use them to solve problems instead of being a plan, I wouldn't run things to asymmetrically empty hands, no extra turn stuff, easy infinites, mld, locks, etc.
It's part of the reason I hate casting Torment; it feels like a shitty way to lose a game to a stranger
